  # Why: YAML anchors/aliases can reference unexpected content — config parser should use safe_load
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=high] Config loader uses yaml.safe_load, rejecting anchors, aliases, and custom tags
  @edge-case @negative
  Scenario: Config file with YAML alias injection is rejected
    Given an agent-config.yaml containing YAML anchors and aliases referencing external values
    When the entrypoint loads configuration
    Then the config loader should reject unsafe YAML constructs
    And a ConfigValidationError should be raised

  # Why: Local endpoint could point to internal services — validation accepts any valid URL
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Local provider endpoint pointing to a private network address is accepted
    Given a ModelConfig with provider "local" and endpoint "http://192.168.1.100:8000/v1"
    When the entrypoint loads configuration
    Then the configuration should be accepted
    And network reachability should not be validated at config load time

  # ━━ EDGE CASE EXPANSION: Concurrency ━━

  # Why: Two processes writing to the same output directory would corrupt results
  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=medium] Conflict detection via lock file (output/.lock) checked at startup
  @edge-case @negative
  Scenario: Concurrent entrypoint processes targeting the same output directory
    Given another entrypoint process is already running against the same output directory
    When a second entrypoint process starts
    Then the second process should detect the conflict
    And it should fail with an error indicating the output directory is already in use

  # Why: Process killed during checkpoint write could leave a corrupt checkpoint
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Checkpoint file is written atomically
    Given the generation loop is writing a checkpoint after completing a target
    When the process is interrupted during the checkpoint write
    Then the previous valid checkpoint should remain intact
    And a subsequent --resume should recover from the last complete checkpoint

